very old Tier'dal families, lost to antiquity. Worship there is technically of Rallos Zek and Cazic-thule --<br>
the Prince of Hate is not followed -- but actually everyone serves the Lord of Mistmoore, willingly or <br>
unwillingly. We are vessels of blood, breeding stock, an investment in the future. The Lord there is a <br>
connoisseur of blood, not surprisingly, and takes great pains to keep the bloodlines pure. <br>
<br>
I would have grown up to be a servitor in the castle, like my mother and father, and eventually, been <br>
made into an undead, depending on my status. Since a little girl, I have lived with blood and the <br>
knowledge of blood. I learned to water our garden with blood. I love flowers. My mother used to say <br>
&quot;blood makes the flowers grow&quot;, and would smile when I brought home small creatures to let their blood <br>
out upon the roses. We had magical fruits that grew, strawberries that gushed sweetly, hotly as blood <br>
once you bit into them, their enchantment revealed. And blood oranges, and pomegranates. On hot <br>
nights in the summer, the vampires would sweat blood, so infused with it were they in this luscious <br>
environment.<br>
<br>
I hunted, and I grew, and I was trained, to the sword, to etiquette, dancing, etc. as a noble. I was told that I *was* noble, that our families had been originally selected for the purity of their Tier'dal heritage, and <br>
that the Lord Mistmoore had picked the three families himself to sojourn to and build his estate. I was <br>
trained to serve what I was taught were my betters, so that I would be pleasing to the Vampires. When <br>
of appropriate age, I was taught the arts of pains, both inflicting and receiving. I was taught patience <br>
and how to bow my head. I was instructed on the service of another's body, both personal and intimate, <br>
and how to yield my own.<br>
<br>
When not otherwise occupied, I spent my time in the valley, often hiding and watching others come and <br>
go. I learned additional fighting techniques by observing foreigners come and attack our people. Strangers<br>
are not welcome in Mistmoore, nearly always. I yearned within to be allowed to go abroad, but only those <br>
who had already been blood-bonded to a vampire were allowed to leave, except for those very very few <br>
who fled the valley. The last person to successfully leave the enclave had been a great-great-aunt of <br>
mine, and I heard that she had taken service to one named Najena, and dwelt within those halls, a legend, <br>
and untouchable by revenge from here.<br>
<br>
When I was sixteen, however, I was selected. Not for blood ritual, but to be made a vampire directly. <br>
The Lord favored hair the color of mine in women, and I had been noticed. I was outraged. I did not wish <br>
to be denied the long life I could expect, only retiring to become immortal at the end. But there was no <br>
appeal. <br>
<br>
I took the only other choice I had, and fled, following a party of barbarians, with two strange women, <br>
the likes I'd never seen before, out of the hills, through the forest, and into the Faydwer. By hiding and <br>
moving quietly from there, I was able to make my way to Neriak, home of the Tier'dal for some time now. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uayida.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayida</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The sexy slave warrior~<br> Tank Girl~</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/4/02 3:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Chapter II:  Neriak</span><hr size=1> Ayida stood on the grass, watching people go to and fro between the guards, the red of their livery standing out against the gray stone. She sighed at the gaping hole in the earth which led to her destination, dreading entering the city. Cities felt like masses of people jammed in too close together, and Freeport, the only city she'd actually been through, had been a living nightmare of everything foreign. She sighed again, thinking that while she could at least understand the &quot;words&quot; that people were using here, that the few Tier'dal she'd spoken to already clearly were so culturally different from her that meanings were not quite the same. <br>
<br>
Her accent was odd sounding to them, she could tell. They looked at her with confusion and suspicion, and<br>
her body language was different too. One actually accused her of being an enchantress using another form,<br>
though the short sword swung under his nose abruptly terminated that discussion.<br>
<br>
With trepidation, she walked up through the guards, unchallenged, and into Neriak. <br>
<br>
After a week, her resources were exhausted. No one would hire her, and few would speak to her more than a word or two. The only offers she'd gotten so far had been crude catcalls on the street, and one tavern owner who wanted her for his brothel, telling her that she might be able to earn room and board if she worked hard.<br>
<br>
There were non-Tier'dal wandering around daily, and the folk of her heritage for the most part seemed<br>
degenerate in their purity. Few showed the strength and focus of purity of will. <br>
<br>
Finally, she went to the building of the warriors guild, for the second time, prepared to be sneered at again. A woman in plate armor was in the lower hall, and surprisingly, spoke to her courteously. &quot;You think you can<br>
fight, little daugher?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I do, my lady. I am willing to prove it in the Arena.&quot;<br>
&quot;Very well then, go and be tested. If you bring a note back for me, I will accept you as a trainee.&quot;<br>
<br>
Her test went well, the trainer lent her several weapons, and was impressed by the speed with which she<br>
could sheath and unsheath them, switching in a moment's notice from two-handed to one-handed. Though<br>
defeated easily, her techniques were commented on favorably, and a sealed note was passed to the Lady of the Cauldron, and a new career was embarked upon, albeit one with little supporrt - trainees were expected to fend totally for themselves, but a roof, even in a barracks was preferable to cold stone streets.<br>
<br>
                            **************<br>
<br>
She was sitting on the edge of the water, in a remote corner of the docks, when she noticed that she was<br>
being observed. The lady was beautiful, and obviously well appointed. She seemed a bit distant, and her voice resonated low and as if from far away. &quot;Who are you, little one?&quot;, she was asked. <br>
<br>
Ayida stood up and curtsied. &quot;I am Ayida, noble Lady.&quot; The woman laughed, with complex overtones of<br>
emotion that Ayida didn't quite understand.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why did you call me here?&quot;, she was asked, again.<br>
<br>
&quot;I called no one, Lady.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Then why am I here? You must have called me. Or something in you did. Tell me of yourself.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ayida proceeded to give an account of herself. The woman nodded, then smiled enigmatically. &quot;How would you like patronage?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I would appreciate it, my lady, if I had anything to offer in return.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;You do, child. Much to offer. You will do as I say, and train, and learn. You will service me, and be of service to me. Do you understand? Will you obey?&quot; <br>
<br>
Ayida considered this carefully. Just getting enough food was difficult. And she had been getting more<br>
attention than she liked recently from several in the city that made her nervous. This lady felt oddly<br>
different, strange and yet familiar, though she could not identify the source. She decided to gamble a bit.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, Lady. I will. If you will shelter and protect me. I swear.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I swear also, child. Learn to be mine, and I will succor you. In token of my oath, accept this armor, and this sword. Now go forth and train. Learn well, learn quick. I may have need of you soon. When you have anything to report, return here, and think of me.&quot; <br>
<br>
Ayida took a tabard of complex weave, greaves, oddly colored, but attractive, and a long thin black sword,<br>
that only reflected dully even under a bright light. She stripped, and put the armor on, belted the sword to her side, and bowed to her new employer. &quot;I am ready, Mistress.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Then go. I have other things to attend to.&quot; <br>
<br>
The strange woman disappeared in front of her. Ayida stared at the ground in front of her, wondering what<br>
had just happened. And what was her employer's name? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uayida.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayida</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The sexy slave warrior~<br> Tank Girl~</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/5/02 12:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Chapter III:  Ayanamii Ekitenshi</span><hr size=1> Another week went by, then two. Ayida spent her time learning the forest of Nektulos, and how to slaughter<br>
the creatures within, what her limits were, and how to fight most efficiently when it was for real. She sat and listened in Taverns and Shops, and made a pest of herself at the Bank, sitting in a corner listening until a guard would tell her to leave. <br>
<br>
An Iksar was having trouble one day at the Bank, looking for a few specific stores, and others standing around were mocking him in Tier'dal. Ayida bowed before him, and offered to show him where the stores were. In perfect Tier'dal, the Iksar replied to her, and Ayida smiled inwardly at the sudden silence in the Bank. He then and there handed her a crystalline two-handed blade, publicly, and Ayida refused it, also publicly, to drive the point of the Lesson the Iksar clearly wished to teach home. After she escorted him to a nearby store, the sword was offered again, privately, and this time Ayida took it, with sincere thanks for his extreme generosity.<br>
<br>
Twice in these weeks, Ayida heard the name &quot;Ayanamii&quot; as a person who hated Tier'dal and dueled them, and eventually found out about a group she belonged to, called &quot;Circle of Sisters&quot;. She traveled to Freeport again, this time to work and train in the yard there, and while there, saw several of this group running around, and later saw two Rogues of this group impersonating Tier'dal in Neriak itself. <br>
<br>
Back in Nektulos, she was one day hailed by a Shadowknight named Shintou Shinai. Ayida talked to him for<br>
several minutes, and was intrigued by his obvious enthusiasm, but his talk of Hate and his obvious fanaticism concerned her. There seemed to be a flaw in this gem, casting confused shadows upon everything he said. He also mentioned this &quot;Ayanamii&quot; peson, and how he would drive her into Hate, but his spirit seemed diffused and unable to concentrate. He eventually hurried off to meet another, and Ayida was left feeling conflicted about this man and his goals. She decided that it was time to investigate the knowledge of Hate. <br>
<br>
It was not something she had much experience with, she preferred to try driving out all emotion while killing,<br>
trying to learn to see the killing from a new perspective, the one the warrior sages speak of in books. She<br>
went and spoke to several disciples of Innoruuk, then decided to test her new knowledge. She traveled again to Freeport, and paid silvers to people in a tavern across from the Circle of Sisters Hall there, in order to hear stories about them. After a day or so, she learned more, and decided to see if she could provoke this Ayanamii.<br>
<br>
Ayida waited until she saw her entering a courtyard in Freeport, then followed her out to the East Commons, calling out &quot;Ayanamii, Daughter of Innoruuk, Shining star in His Eyes, I come to seek a Lesson in Hate from you&quot;. The monk stopped, then turned rapidly and denied worshipping Innoruuk, clearly enraged. Ayida laughed to herself, and continued the dicussion, &quot;But oh Monk, Innoruuk favors you. All Tier'dal know of the Hatred of Ayanamii, and we are told to seek you out for Lessons. &quot;<br>
<br>
The monk responded, &quot;The only lesson I will teach you is how to lie in the ground.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I am young, but I am willing to duel you, Monk. You shall surely defeat me, but I would be humbly grateful of the Lesson from one such as yourself. If I can go back to Neriak and say &quot;the great monk, Ayanamii, Child of Hate, defeated me in a duel today&quot;, my status would rise far more than if I defeated any number of Tier'dal of my own rank&quot;. All lies of course, but by now the monk was sweating, and trembling with rage, a fey light in her eyes. <br>
<br>
Ayida smiled again to herself. It was hardly sport to provoke this monk. From the tavern across from the<br>
guildhall of the Circle, She had learnt of the duel between Shintou and Ayanamii, and the results thereof, of<br>
Shintou's fall to weakness, and Ayanamii's near madness at the release of her own Rage. But already Ayida<br>
had duplicated the Shintou's effort, albeit with foreknowledge of the way it went the last time, and losing in a duel to someone ages above her (she was only season 6) in experience was a small price to pay for<br>
satisfaction. Indeed the duel, when finally provoked by the Monk in her anger, lasted only 3 or 4 blows. So the monk was left looking angry and shamed, and Ayida began the slow journey back from Neriak to reclaim her broken body.<br>
<br>
Ayida decided to tell others of this duel, and incite them to provoke the monk as well, particularly other young Tier'dal, but anyone would do. If enough came to her, calling her Daughter of Innoruuk, Child of Hate, and asked for lessons, it might eventually drive the Ayanamii permanently mad. Ayida decided that Hate was an excellent way to control others, but that its Lessons might well be taken in moderation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uayida.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayida</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The sexy slave warrior~<br> Tank Girl~</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/5/02 12:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/frage81292frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Chapter IV:  Blood</span><hr size=1> (note:  this chapter is presented here in edited form, due to the content of the original chapter).<br>
<br>
The next several weeks were a turmoil. <br>
<br>
Mistress Dalninil had given her goals to meet for training, and the few times she failed to meet them she was<br>
lashed and tortured.<br>
<br>
She saw Dalninil rarely, and in odd circumstances. She would appear suddenly and would disappear as rapidly.  Once she made an odd comment &quot;Oops, summoned,&quot; and simply vanished. There was something here that Ayida could not figure out, but was sure that it would become clear eventually. More equipment showed up and was bestowed upon her whenever her goals were exceeded.<br>
<br>
Ayida began doing small things for her mistress, dressing her, and tending to her bath, sleeping at the foot of Dalninil's bed when she wasn't off camping in some remote location after hunting. She kept Dalninil's chamber tidy, but rarely saw anyone else, and frequently slept alone in the room. In fact, Dalninil was always there at the beginning, or when she woke up, but never both.<br>
<br>
There were other folk she met, new friends. She began hunting with a young necromancer, who talked of their becoming friends. She found two Tier'dal, a young priestess of Innoruuk and an Enchantress, who had traveled to Ogguk and contract bound a young Ogre to them. They were glad of her company, and the hunting was profitable. She met the strange shadowknight, Eldraed, who seemed fond of her, and the Ogre, Bramurg, who clearly wanted her to join Norrath's Soldiers of Chaos.<br>
<br>
She saw more new races and strange folk than she had ever seen before. Their languages were strange, and their behavior even more so. Few seemed to understand the concepts of honor and duty, and some were clearly lacking in manners and breeding, but there were enough others who did, of human and ogre and troll races, that Ayida sometimes found herself with strange hunting companions that she could rarely<br>
communicate with. <br>
<br>
Then one night Dalninil showed up and said &quot;What will you do for me, Pet?&quot; (She frequently called Ayida Pet,<br>
though in the few times they'd been in public called her &quot;my servant&quot; or &quot;my slave&quot;.) Ayida knew the correct<br>
response, and answered &quot;Anything Mistress&quot;. &quot;We'll find out tonight, my Pet. Are you ready.&quot;<br>
                            <br>
Adrenaline surged through Ayida's veins, and her blood pounded within her. Hadn't she already been doing<br>
everything she was told? What test was this?<br>
<br>
The &quot;are you ready&quot; had not been a question, and Ayida merely bowed her head, and followed Dalninil. They<br>
