through various common zones, the two of them slaughtering all in their path, leaving an abattoir of bodies in their wake.<br>
<br>
Upon query, she discovered that he had not found his shadowknight apprentice. And this time he was looking at her differently. He was even more personable, more charming that he had been before. And so they laughed, and he took her on a few picnics.<br>
<br>
The first one was to Mistmoore. They slaughtered their way into the graveyard and even into the castle itself.  He watched her as she slew the knight within and took the crested pauldron and rested it upon her shoulders, a token of her return to this place of her birth, and the minor victory of letting Mayong's minions know that not only was she still alive, but prospering.<br>
<br>
Their luncheon was had upon a blanket of vah shir and kerran hides that Ayida had made from some of her<br>
conquests, a soft dappled fur of several colors and and patterns. <br>
<br>
Eldraed brought forth gourmet delights, one after the other. They finished with candied spider and winter falls wine, and she admired his skill at cooking and smiled at the delight he felt in such an activity. <br>
<br>
For a moment she fell into a reverie, seeing in her mind's eye the dread shadowknight's face reflected in the<br>
dark red glow of the fires as he chuckled over the scene before him as he prodded the implements in the fire<br>
with evil humor. She imagined him uttering a prayer to his god Innoruuk, finally nodding with satisfaction at his success and withdrawing from the coals the pan, now laden with brownies, the bubbling chocolate seething within, as he placed them to cool in the snow while contemplating the cheerful slaughter of those that he had slain that day to achieve this precious goal. <br>
<br>
Ayida laughed out loud, and seeing the query in her knight's eye described the scene to him. They both<br>
laughed in the soft breeze of the afternoon there in the graveyard as the sun crept towards the horizon.<br>
<br>
On their way back out that evening, Equestrielle, who had bothered Ayida more than once passing through<br>
the Faydark, crested a hill, heading straight for them. Eldraed turned and cast a spell at her, seeking combat, but the horse was smarter than Ayida had thought, and it turned and ran as though it had devils after it, which in a sense it did.<br>
<br>
**<br>
It was clear that their relationship was changing, but Ayida was surprisingly slow to catch on. One day<br>
someone asked her how long that Eldraed had been 'sweet on her', and the light dawned! He was. And she<br>
liked him too. Ayida wasn't used to dealing with males much, and the discovery was surprising, as was the joy she felt the next time she saw him.<br>
<br>
Their next picnic was on a remote island in the Ocean of Tears, with a small stop-over to slay most of the<br>
Sisters of Erollisi on Sister Isle. Once again the food was excellent, and this time the talk progressed to<br>
themselves and what relationship that might be developing. <br>
<br>
Ayida explained about her bonding with Dalninil, but wasn't sure that he understood it really. Those who are<br>
not familiar with the ancient blood-rituals often don't clearly see how they bind the souls together as well as<br>
the bodies. Ayida was of, and belonged to, Dalninil now. And in a similar sense, Dalninil was also her. Cutting<br>
the head from the body damages both, and Ayida tried to explain how though she was free to pursue such<br>
relationships as did meet her mistress's favor, that she would always belong to her.<br>
<br>
Eldraed talked about buying her, then finding some other method of freeing her, and finally Ayida simply asked him to seek Dalninil's permission to court her, and pointed out that checking in with her Ilharess, Genashai might also be a good idea.<br>
<br>
He did go and do this, and Ayida found herself granted permission to see this knight romantically. Of course<br>
she had also consulted with her Mistress and her Ilharess herself, but it was important to her that he go ask.  He was already a great lord in Neriak, and had recently become the Emissary of War as well.<br>
<br>
So it came to pass that Eldraed and Ayida found themselves smiling at one another in public, and having quiet times together to enjoy their hobbies, mostly food and killing. He was busy with his responsibilities, as she was with hers, and often they would not see one another for days, but when they did, it was always special. <br>
<br>
And then one day Eldraed came to her with another quest, which surprised her. He told her that this one<br>
would be hard, but that the rewards would be worth it, he hoped. After all the other quests she had<br>
performed, this one would be more difficult than any, and would take her a long time in all likelihood, but that he hoped that she would persevere through it. <br>
<br>
She smiled and accepted, feeling that this was yet another of his idiosyncrasies. They were romantically<br>
involved, but if it pleased him to continue their old game, she would. <br>
<br>
First he went and concealed himself within the Great Divide and told her to seek him out. The Great Divide is<br>
not the easiest place to find someone, she told him, and he smiled. &quot;use all available resources&quot; became the<br>
refrain that she would eventually groan to hear.<br>
<br>
Ayida knew few trackers, and cared to seek the aid of fewer, and none were currently available anyway. That truly would have made it an easy task. Instead, the sorceress Sindell (who would often show up and take her on shopping trips all over Norrath) came to her plea, and hearing about the task answered with amusement that she would be pleased to assist. <br>
<br>
Ayida finally found him in the cave of the shardwurms. He would not smile at her, not greet her with a hug as he normally would. His manner was nearly regal, and distant as the oracles of Norrath often are, those who give out adventures to the willing. She actually found herself saying &quot;What giants?&quot; &quot;What about the<br>
dwarves?&quot;, and laughed to herself.<br>
<br>
It devolved that this was a task to help the dwarves against the giants. Well enough. They wanted frost giant meat to feed the wurms, and frost giant toes, heads, and even perhaps some helms to give evidence of her active assistance.<br>
<br>
The task was not difficult particularly, but involved a bit of time, and several days passed while Ayida slew<br>
giants. Her return offer of a stack of frost giant steaks was refused, as the wurms needed uncooked meat,<br>
she was told. A sigh and some more killing resulted. During this time Ayida met several new friends, folks who were also hunting the Giants, also folk of her House helped her out, including her Ilharess, Genashai. Ayida always was honored by the times that her Ilharess would come and hunt with her, it was a mark of favor that she treasured.<br>
<br>
Upon the completion of this, she returned to the caves and was told to meet him at the foot of Dain IV, who would give her another task. This time, she was asked for materials for bow strings to aid the dwarves. They wanted 100' of some kind of magical velious kelp or something. Queries and research led nowhere until she finally discovered a reference to 100' of waterproof rope that was obtainable from a shipwreck in the Cobalt Scar. Again, Sindell was a great help to her, and shortly Ayida delivered the rope to Eldraed at the foot of Dain. A Bow of the Huntsman was an interim reward as thanks for assisting the war effort, a lovely gift indeed.<br>
<br>
The 3rd task now took her into another phase of the quest. Having assisted the dwarves sufficiently, she was told, the dragons were now willing to treat with her and see if she was worthy of their notice. It was the desire of the dragon Rolandal, she was told, to have evidence of her faithfulness. Bring to him the symbol of the loyalty of the goblin king of permafrost to the renegade Vox, and she would be rewarded with a gift and her next task.<br>
<br>
Ayida cringed at this one. Not only was it going to be difficult to journey once more into Permafrost to obtain this item, but she was rapidly approaching the point where the gods would deem a reward for the slaying of the goblin king unworthy of her. And then there was that afternoon's hunting in Skyshrine, wherein she had slain enough of the guardians of that place for any favor she might have had with the dragons to have fallen.<br>
<br>
Rescued again by the members of her House, the symbol of Loyalty to Vox was easily obtainable. Several<br>
offered her this gift that they had already obtained, but Braellar was the one who handed it to her one<br>
afternoon as they shared an ale.<br>
<br>
Being allowed back into the presence of the dragon Rolandal was another matter. Ayida hunted giants. And<br>
hunted giants. And hunted giants, in Great Divide, in the Eastern Wastes, and finally in Kael Drakkel itself for<br>
weeks. Time after time, she traveled at great risk to where she could gain a glimpse of a dragon to see if her presence would be tolerated, and time after time, she journeyed back to kill more giants, her heart heavy at the afternoon of slaughter that she was beginning to regret. <br>
<br>
Finally, one day, the guardian creatures of Cobalt Scar would tolerate her presence. She laughed in the sea<br>
breeze and the snow, as a cobalt drake glided directly above her, its wings buffeting the air around her.<br>
<br>
Taking the symbol, she met Eldraed standing between the feet of Rolandal, and she saluted, then gave the<br>
symbol to the dragon.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well done&quot;, said Eldraed. &quot;Rolandal has these two pieces of armor for you as tokens of his cognizance of your work. Are you ready for your next task?&quot; <br>
<br>
This 4th stage was daunting. The dragons of Skyshrine were unhappy with a troll, a profiteer on the black<br>
market, who was a renegade from Grobb. His name was Rungupp, and among his other misdeeds, he was guilty of stealing dragon eggs and selling them on the black market. &quot;Bring me the head of Rungupp, and restore a  lost dragon egg to us. You must deliver it to the commanders of Skyshrine, specifically Lawyla, Ralgyn, and Jalicn.&quot;, translated Eldraed as the dragon rumbled in a tongue not known to Ayida.<br>
<br>
Rungupp. Ayida knew immediately who this miscreant was and where to find him. After that it was a matter of hiring successive groups of adventurers until she finally was able to hire a pair from Erudin Palace, an<br>
enchantress and a wizardess of the 4th ranks of that place. They slew him and took his head, and Ayida paid them and went on her way. A simple matter, but one that involved days of hanging around Paineel and the Warrens, looking for someone who was willing to cooperate with a Tier'dal. For fun, Ayida slew every kobold in the Warrens, 3 times, walking from one end to the other and back again. It was necessary to skip several and come back later, as some of the kobolds were being hunted by others, but eventually Ayida slew them all, as well as the overgrown tadpole and the funny bear that lurked in their respective lairs. <br>
<br>
Ayida searched the black market. Time and time again, there would be a lead to someone who may have had one of these things, but every lead petered out. Dragon eggs were a rare commodity to begin with, and few would admit to even having seen one of these things. Finally Ayida found a contact in Grobb who had one. In exchange for a stack of HEHE meat (a sausage made of High Elf, Erudite, and Human), he would exchange with her. Killing enough high elves, humans, and erudites was both fun and a pain, as so many things often are. She was thankful that her own studies of cooking allowed her to make this food, and even finally sampled some herself. An interesting flavor, but crude in actuality. And substituting halfling for human was an experiment that just didn't work out. Their livers were too pickled by alcohol or something.  Ayida decided to stick to high elven veal. <br>
<br>
When she got to Grobb, however, the contact had fled from the authorities. Ayida caught up with him in<br>
Cobalt Scar, and after relieving him of his burden, relieved him of his life as well, then taking her egg,<br>
proceeded to Skyshrine. <br>
<br>
Wherein she promply got lost in the maze that is the palace of the dragons. Maps were difficult to find at all, those few that did exist were partial, and the maze itself was deeply confusing. And maze it was. In fact, there was a multi-level maze in the middle of it, wherein she saw not another living soul. After a seeming eternity of wandering these vast and intricate halls, she finally made it to Lawyla. And then there was Eldraed again, smiling at her. &quot;Well done. You have only one more step to take, Ayida. Meet me at the foot of Commander Sontalak at the Gates of the Temple of Veeshan, and you shall have proved your mettle as a warrioress and a Tier'dal.&quot; &quot;And while you're here, if you're careful, I might be able to get you a sneak peak at Yelinak. Do not approach too closely, or your life will be forfeit, however.&quot;. <br>
<br>
And so Ayida got to see the legendary king of the dragons, who glowered within his vasty hall, and was glad<br>
that he did not see her peeking through the gate. The most fun however, was ice skating in the halls with<br>
Eldraed, doing spins and figure 8s and generally gliding around laughing like a silly person. &quot;What a wonderful<br>
place for an ice-skating party&quot;, she mused as she followed him back to the courtyard of the dragons.<br>
<br>
It was so fun that the difficulty of obtaining the final step was obscured until the next morning when she<br>
woke up. And then the weight of it hit her. Not only had she never been to the Western Wastes, but just<br>
getting through the Siren's Grotto was going to be a severe test for one of her experience. She would need<br>
significant help. And finally, help she got. Once more, her family in Sel'quar came to her aid and assistance.<br>
<br>
Armed with some extra potions for security, the wizard Zeff, and her Ilharn Braellar accompanied her to Cobalt Scar, and escorted her through Siren's Grotto. In her foolishness, she forgot that her Ilharess Genashai had offered to help, and woefully neglected the very great assistance that such a powerful mage could have granted, as well as the honor of her company on such an enterprise.<br>
<br>
After they made it to the Western Wastes, Braellar led her on the perilous run to the Temple of Veeshan, and she knew that his presence was not welcome by the dragons. So when they came to the point where they overlooked the great canyon, she prevailed upon him to stay and wait for her, which he did reluctantly. &quot;Your bravery is already great, my lord, please allow me this last step on my own&quot;, she said, and he acquiesced gracefully.<br>
<br>
Waiting for her yet again, at the feet of the ugliest dragon that Ayida had ever seen, was Eldraed. He smiled at her, and she suddenly was very excited. <br>
<br>
&quot;Welcome Ayida Winnower. Know that on this day, you have succeeded at the Test of Lamentation and<br>
Defiance. Your prowess as a warrior and a leader are confirmed, and as such you shall be rewarded. First,<br>
here is a scroll. By my authority as a representative of The Dead, you are hereby granted Neriak Citizenship<br>
with all the rights that entails. No longer shall you be a statusless person in Neriak. And take as well these<br>
two blades, whose names reflect the Test which you have conquered.&quot;<br>
<br>
The blades were lovely and efficient looking. She sheathed them at her side, resolving to take a look at them later. <br>
<br>
But the other thing revealed to her was why this quest at all, what was in the back of his mind the whole<br>
time. He was seeking for a way to let her earn herself something that he wished to give her - rights and<br>
status as a Neriak Citizen in her own regard, not just as a pet to her Mistress, Dalninil Venorsh. Though she<br>
still belonged to Dalninil, willingly bonded by the ancient blood rites that cannot be set aside, Eldraed had<br>
found a way to allow her to feel secure about her relationship with him as well. <br>
<br>
It was a noble gift, and as she made her way back to the Cobalt, she thought about how nervous he must<br>
have been, daring to set a Tier'dal female such a task, and still hoping that she would succeed, for both their sakes. Now she knew the answer to the question which her Ilharess had so foresightedly asked her - why was he daring to order a Tier'dal female around in such a manner, what were his motivations?<br>
<br>
